org.magnos.trie

Class TrieNode<S,T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.magnos.trie.TrieNode<S,T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.Map.Entry<S,T>

    public class TrieNode<S,T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Map.Entry<S,T>
    A TrieNode is an Entry in a Trie that stores the sequence (key), value, the starting and ending indices into the sequence, the number of children in this node, and the parent to this node.

    There are three types of TrieNodes and each have special properties.

    1. Root
      • getStart() == getEnd() == 0
      • getValue() == null
      • getKey() == getSequence() == null
    2. Naked Branch
      • getStart() < getEnd()
      • getValue() == null
      • getKey() == getSequence() == (a key of one of it's children or a past child, ignore)
    3. Valued (Branch or Leaf)
      • getStart() < getEnd()
      • getValue() == non-null value passed into Trie.put(Object, Object)
      • getKey() == getSequence() == a non-null key passed into Trie.put(Object, Object)

    You can tell a valued branch or leaf apart by getChildCount(), if it returns 0 then it's a leaf, otherwise it's a branch.

    Author:
    Philip Diffenderfer

      • split

        protected TrieNode<S,T> split(int index,
                              T newValue,
                              TrieSequencer<S> sequencer)
        Splits this node at the given relative index and returns the TrieNode with the sequence starting at index. The returned TrieNode has this node's sequence, value, and children. The returned TrieNode is also the only child of this node when this method returns.
        Parameters:
        index - The relative index (starting at 0 and going to end - start - 1) in the sequence.
        newValue - The new value of this node.
        sequencer - The sequencer used to add the returned node to this node.
        Returns:
        The reference to the child node created that's sequence starts at index.
